\section{\texorpdfstring{Proposed
Wording\hyperref[proposed-wording]{}}{Proposed Wording}}\label{proposed-wording}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Manual Paragraph
Numbers\hyperref[manual-paragraph-numbers]{}}{Manual Paragraph Numbers}}\label{manual-paragraph-numbers}

\pnum{2} An expression is \emph{potentially evaluated} unless it is an
unevaluated operand (7.2) or a subexpression thereof. The set of
\emph{potential results} of an expression \VERB|\NormalTok{e}| is
defined as follows:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \pnum{(2.1)} If \VERB|\NormalTok{e}| is an
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\emph{id-expression}}| (7.5.4), the set contains only
  \VERB|\NormalTok{e}|.
\item
  \pnum{(2.2)} If \VERB|\NormalTok{e}| is a subscripting operation
  (7.6.1.1) with an array operand, the set contains the potential
  results of that operand.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Automatic Paragraph
Numbers\hyperref[automatic-paragraph-numbers]{}}{Automatic Paragraph Numbers}}\label{automatic-paragraph-numbers}

\pnum{1} \VERB|\NormalTok{\#.}| automatically starts at
\VERB|\DecValTok{1}|.

\pnum{2} Another \VERB|\NormalTok{\#.}| automatically continues to
\VERB|\DecValTok{2}|.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.1)} Nested bullet list also get automatic numbering.
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{(}\FloatTok{2.1}\OperatorTok{)}|.

  {[}\ldots{]}
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.5)} Example of skipping. Pin to \VERB|\NormalTok{5.}|, yields
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{(}\FloatTok{2.5}\OperatorTok{)}|.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.6)} Continues to
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{(}\FloatTok{2.6}\OperatorTok{)}|.

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \pnum{(2.6.1)} Nested nested bullet list should just work
    \VERB|\NormalTok{(2.6.1)}|.

    {[}\ldots{]}
  \end{itemize}

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \pnum{(2.6.9)} \VERB|\NormalTok{9.}| here will bring us to
    \VERB|\NormalTok{(2.6.9)}|.
  \end{itemize}

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \pnum{(2.6.x)} \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}| here will be
    \VERB|\NormalTok{(2.6.x)}|.
  \item
    \pnum{(2.6.x)} Another \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}| here will also be
    \VERB|\NormalTok{(2.6.x)}|.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\pnum{3} \VERB|\NormalTok{\#.}| automatically continues to
\VERB|\DecValTok{3}|.

Also handle code blocks within a list item:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DataTypeTok{int}\NormalTok{ main}\OperatorTok{()}\NormalTok{;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\pnum{x} Use \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}| to skip a paragraph number.

\pnum{x} Another \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}| assigned \VERB|\NormalTok{x}|.

\pnum{4} \VERB|\NormalTok{\#.}| automatically continues to
\VERB|\DecValTok{4}|.

{[}\ldots{]}

\pnum{17} Pin with \VERB|\NormalTok{17.}|.

{\color[HTML]{006e28}\pnum{x} \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}| is mainly to skip
numbering in \VERB|\NormalTok{add}|.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(x.1)} Nested bullet within an \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}|. This will
  be (x.1).
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(x.x)} Nested \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}| within an
  \VERB|\NormalTok{x)}|. This will be (x.x).
\end{itemize}

\pnum{x} Second added paragraph.}

{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\pnum{18} \VERB|\NormalTok{\#.}| here will be 18
after the skips.

{[}\ldots{]}

\pnum{24} Skip and pin again, e.g.~\VERB|\NormalTok{24.}|.}

\pnum{25} Automatically continue to 25.

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsubsection*{\texorpdfstring{General {4.1.1
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.compliance.general}{{[}intro.compliance.general{]}}}\hyperref[general-intro.compliance.general]{}}{General 4.1.1 {[}intro.compliance.general{]}}}\label{general-intro.compliance.general}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{General {4.1.1
{{[}intro.compliance.general{]}}}{}}

\pnum{1} The set of \emph{diagnosable rules} consists of all syntactic
and semantic rules in this document except for those rules containing an
explicit notation that ``no diagnostic is required'' or which are
described as resulting in ``undefined behavior''.

\pnum{2} Although this document states only requirements on C++
implementations, those requirements are often easier to understand if
they are phrased as requirements on programs, parts of programs, or
execution of programs. Such requirements have the following meaning:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.1)} If a program contains no violations of the rules in
  \href{https://eel.is/c++draft/lex}{{[}lex{]}} through
  \href{https://eel.is/c++draft/exec}{{[}exec{]}} as well as those
  specified in \href{https://eel.is/c++draft/depr}{{[}depr{]}}, a
  conforming implementation shall accept and correctly execute that
  program, except when the implementation's limitations (see below) are
  exceeded.
\item
  \pnum{(2.2)} If a program contains a violation of a rule for which no
  diagnostic is required, this document places no requirement on
  implementations with respect to that program.
\item
  \pnum{(2.3)} Otherwise, if a program contains

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \pnum{(2.3.1)} a violation of any diagnosable rule,
  \item
    \pnum{(2.3.2)} a preprocessing translation unit with a
    \VERB|\PreprocessorTok{\#warning}| preprocessing directive
    (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/cpp.error}{{[}cpp.error{]}}),
  \item
    \pnum{(2.3.3)} an occurrence of a construct described in this
    document as ``conditionally-supported'' when the implementation does
    not support that construct, or
  \item
    \pnum{(2.3.4)} a contract assertion
    (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.contract.eval}{{[}basic.contract.eval{]}})
    evaluated with a checking semantic in a manifestly
    constant-evaluated context
    (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/expr.const.defns}{{[}expr.const.defns{]}})
    resulting in a contract violation,
  \end{itemize}

  a conforming implementation shall issue at least one diagnostic
  message.
\end{itemize}

{{{[} \emph{Note:} }During template argument deduction and substitution,
certain constructs that in other contexts require a diagnostic are
treated differently; see
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/temp.deduct}{{[}temp.deduct{]}}.{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}

Furthermore, a conforming implementation shall not accept

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \pnum{(2.4)} a preprocessing translation unit containing a
  \VERB|\PreprocessorTok{\#error}| preprocessing directive
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/cpp.error}{{[}cpp.error{]}}),
\item
  \pnum{(2.5)} a translation unit with a
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\emph{static\_assert-declaration}}| that fails
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/dcl.pre}{{[}dcl.pre{]}}), or
\item
  \pnum{(2.6)} a contract assertion evaluated with a terminating
  semantic
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.contract.eval}{{[}basic.contract.eval{]}})
  in a manifestly constant-evaluated context
  (\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/expr.const.defns}{{[}expr.const.defns{]}})
  resulting in a contract violation.
\end{itemize}

\pnum{3} For classes and class templates, the library Clauses specify
partial definitions. Private members are not specified, but each
implementation shall supply them to complete the definitions according
to the description in the library Clauses.

\subsubsection*{\texorpdfstring{Diagnostic directives {15.9
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/cpp.error}{{[}cpp.error{]}}}\hyperref[diagnostic-directives-cpp.error]{}}{Diagnostic directives 15.9 {[}cpp.error{]}}}\label{diagnostic-directives-cpp.error}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Diagnostic directives {15.9
{{[}cpp.error{]}}}{}}

\pnum{1} A preprocessing directive of the form

\begin{quote}
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{\# error \emph{pp-tokens\textsubscript{opt}} \emph{new-line}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{quote}

renders the program ill-formed. A preprocessing directive of the form

\begin{quote}
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\PreprocessorTok{\# warning \emph{pp-tokens\textsubscript{opt}} \emph{new-line}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\end{quote}

requires the implementation to produce at least one diagnostic message
for the preprocessing translation unit
(\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/intro.compliance.general}{{[}intro.compliance.general{]}}).

\pnum{2} \emph{Recommended practice}: Any diagnostic message caused by
either of these directives should include the specified sequence of
preprocessing tokens.

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Wording
Changes\hyperref[wording-changes]{}}{Wording Changes}}\label{wording-changes}

Large changes are \VERB|\OperatorTok{:::}\NormalTok{ add}| for
additions, \VERB|\OperatorTok{:::}\NormalTok{ rm}| for removals.

\begin{quote}
Modify section {28.5.5
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/format.functions}{{[}format.functions{]}}}:

{\color[HTML]{006e28}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{template\textless{}class... Args\textgreater{}}
\NormalTok{  string format(const locale\& loc, string\_view fmt, const Args\&... args);}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\emph{Returns:}
\VERB|\NormalTok{vformat(loc, fmt, make\_format\_args(args...))}|.}
\end{quote}

Small, inline changes are done with
\VERB|\NormalTok{[new text]\{.add\}}| or
\VERB|\NormalTok{[old text]\{.rm\}}|.

Substitutions can be written as
\VERB|\NormalTok{[old text](new text)\{.sub\}}|. This is essentially
just a short-form for
\VERB|\NormalTok{[old text]\{.rm\}[new text]\{.add\}}|.

The optional \emph{attribute-specifier-seq} appertains to the
{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{general-label}}}}}.
The only use of a {{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label with an
\emph{identifier}}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{label}}}}} is as
the target of a \VERB|\ControlFlowTok{goto}|,
{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{break}|, or
\VERB|\NormalTok{continue}|}}}. No two
{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{label}}}}}s
in a function shall have the same \emph{identifier}. A
{{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{label}}}{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\emph{general-label}}}}}
can be used {{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{in a \VERB|\NormalTok{goto}|
statement}}} before its introduction by a \emph{labeled-statement}.

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1481}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.8519}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Specifier}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Replacement}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{a}| & The locale's abbreviated weekday
name. If the value does not contain a valid weekday,
{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{\VERB|\NormalTok{setstate(ios::failbit)}| is
called}}} {{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{format\_error}|
is thrown}}}. \\
\VERB|\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{A}| & The locale's full weekday name.
If the value does not contain a valid weekday,
{{\color[HTML]{bf0303}\sout{\VERB|\NormalTok{setstate(ios::failbit)}| is
called}}} {{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{format\_error}|
is thrown}}}. \\
\end{longtable}
}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Grammar
Changes\hyperref[grammar-changes]{}}{Grammar Changes}}\label{grammar-changes}

\begin{quote}
\emph{selection-statement:}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{if} \KeywordTok{constexpr}|\emph{\textsubscript{opt}}
\VERB|\OperatorTok{(}| \emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{condition} \VERB|\OperatorTok{)}| \emph{statement}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{if} \KeywordTok{constexpr}|\emph{\textsubscript{opt}}
\VERB|\OperatorTok{(}| \emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{condition} \VERB|\OperatorTok{)}| \emph{statement}
\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{else}| \emph{statement}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\ControlFlowTok{switch} \OperatorTok{(}|
\emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}} \emph{condition}
\VERB|\OperatorTok{)}| \emph{statement}\\
\strut ~~~~{{\color[HTML]{006e28}\uline{\VERB|\NormalTok{inspect}|
\VERB|\NormalTok{constexpr}|\textsubscript{\emph{opt}}
\VERB|\NormalTok{(}| \emph{init-statement\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{condition} \VERB|\NormalTok{)}| \VERB|\NormalTok{\{}|
\emph{inspect-case-seq} \VERB|\NormalTok{\}}|}}}

{\color[HTML]{006e28}

\emph{inspect-case-seq:}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{inspect-case}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{inspect-case-seq} \emph{inspect-case}

\emph{inspect-case:}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{attribute-specifier-seq\textsubscript{opt}}
\emph{inspect-pattern} \emph{inspect-guard\textsubscript{opt}}
\VERB|\NormalTok{:}| \emph{statement}

\emph{inspect-pattern:}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{wildcard-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{identifier-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{constant-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{structured-binding-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{alternative-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{binding-pattern}\\
\strut ~~~~\emph{extractor-pattern}

\emph{inspect-guard:}\\
\strut ~~~~\VERB|\NormalTok{if (}| \emph{expression}
\VERB|\NormalTok{)}|

}
\end{quote}

\section{\texorpdfstring{Stable
Names\hyperref[stable-names]{}}{Stable Names}}\label{stable-names}

Stable names are written as
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[}\NormalTok{basic}\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{life}\OperatorTok{]\{.}\NormalTok{sref}\OperatorTok{\}}|,
and renders as {6.8.4
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}}.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{{-}}| or
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{unnumbered}| class to omit the section
  number.
\item
  Add the \VERB|\OperatorTok{.}\NormalTok{title}| class to add the
  section title.
\end{itemize}

Examples:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5811}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4189}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]}| &
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]/1}| &
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#1}{{[}basic.life{]}/1} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]/2.1}| &
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#2.1}{{[}basic.life{]}/2.1} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]\{.sref\}}| & {6.8.4
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]\{.sref\}/1}| & {6.8.4
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#1}{{[}basic.life{]}/1}} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]\{.sref .title\}}| & {6.8.4 Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]\{.sref .title\}/1}| & {6.8.4 Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#1}{{[}basic.life{]}/1}} \\
\end{longtable}
}

Also supported:

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5811}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4189}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Markdown Source}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\centering\arraybackslash\textbf{Rendered Output}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life\#1]\{.sref\}}| & {6.8.4
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life\#1}{{[}basic.life{]}/1}} \\
\VERB|\NormalTok{[basic.life]\{{-} .sref .title\}}| & {Lifetime
\href{https://eel.is/c++draft/basic.life}{{[}basic.life{]}}} \\
\end{longtable}
}

\section{\texorpdfstring{Notes\hyperref[notes]{}}{Notes}}\label{notes}

There are three supported styles of note:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Use the \VERB|\NormalTok{note}| class for notes that are expected to
  appear in the specification wording

  \begin{Shaded}
  \begin{Highlighting}[]
  \NormalTok{[Notes will look like this]\{.note\}}
  \end{Highlighting}
  \end{Shaded}

  {{{[} \emph{Note:} }Notes will look like
  this{ --- \emph{end note} {]}}}
\item
  Use the \VERB|\NormalTok{ednote}| for editorial notes, these will be
  formatted as

  \begin{Shaded}
  \begin{Highlighting}[]
  \NormalTok{[Editorial notes are important]\{.ednote\}}
  \end{Highlighting}
  \end{Shaded}

  {{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Editor\textquotesingle s note: Editorial
  notes are important {]}}}
\item
  Use \VERB|\NormalTok{draftnote}| to include text that is intended as
  questions or information for reviews and working groups.

  \begin{Shaded}
  \begin{Highlighting}[]
  \NormalTok{[Drafting notes can be used to provide comments for reviewers that are explicitly not to be}
  \NormalTok{ included in the specification.]\{.draftnote\}}

  \NormalTok{ [It is also possible to indicate the a note is for}
  \NormalTok{ a specific \textasciigrave{}audience\textasciigrave{} via this optional attribute.]\{.draftnote audience="the reader"\}}
  \end{Highlighting}
  \end{Shaded}

  {{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Drafting note: Drafting notes can be used to
  provide comments for reviewers that are explicitly not to be included
  in the specification. {]}}}

  {{\color[HTML]{0000ff}{[} Drafting note for the reader: It is also
  possible to indicate the a note is for a specific
  \VERB|\NormalTok{audience}| via this optional attribute. {]}}}
\end{itemize}

\section{\texorpdfstring{Citation\hyperref[citation]{}}{Citation}}\label{citation}

Automatic references are written as
\VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{N4762}\OperatorTok{]}| and renders as
\href{https://wg21.link/n4762}{{[}N4762{]}}. Anything in
\url{https://wg21.link/index.yaml} are linked automatically.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{N}| Papers (e.g.,
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{N3887}\OperatorTok{]}| →
  \href{https://wg21.link/n3887}{{[}N3887{]}})
\item
  \VERB|\NormalTok{P}| Papers (e.g.,
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{P1371R1}\OperatorTok{]}| →
  \href{https://wg21.link/p1371r1}{{[}P1371R1{]}})
\item
  CWG Issues (e.g.,
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{CWG1234}\OperatorTok{]}| →
  \href{https://wg21.link/cwg1234}{{[}CWG1234{]}})
\item
  LWG Issues (e.g.,
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{LWG1234}\OperatorTok{]}| →
  \href{https://wg21.link/lwg1234}{{[}LWG1234{]}})
\item
  Github Edits (e.g,
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{EDIT1234}\OperatorTok{]}| →
  \href{https://wg21.link/edit1234}{{[}EDIT1234{]}})
\item
  Standing Documents (e.g.,
  \VERB|\OperatorTok{[@}\NormalTok{SD6}\OperatorTok{]}| →
  \href{https://wg21.link/sd6}{{[}SD6{]}})
\end{itemize}

You may also write \VERB|\NormalTok{[@P2996R8]\{.title\}}| to include
the title of the paper, and renders as:
{\href{https://wg21.link/p2996r8}{{[}P2996R8{]} (Reflection for
C++26)}}.

